est Flanders, Belgium","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Gérard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It is derived from <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’ + <i>hard</i> ‘brave, hardy, strong’. In the later Middle Ages this was a more common name than   Gerald  , with which it was sometimes confused. Nowadays it is less common, surviving mainly among Roman Catholics, in honour of the many saints of this name."],"variants":[{"name":"Gerrard","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Gerard  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Jerrard","meanings":["Rare variant spelling of   Gerard  , probably influenced by the form of the modern surname, if not a transferred use."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of the various boys' names with the first syllable <i>Ed-</i>, especially   Edward ."],"variants":[{"name":"Edward","meanings":["From an Old English personal name derived from <i>ēad</i> ‘prosperity, riches’ + <i>weard</i> ‘guard’. This has been one of the most successful of all Old English names, in frequent use from before the Conquest to the present day, and even being exported into other European languages. It was the name of three Anglo-Saxon kings and has been borne by eight kings of England since the Norman Conquest. It is also the name of the youngest son of  Queen Elizabeth II . The most influential early bearer was  King Edward  the Confessor (  ?1002–66 ; ruled  1042–66 ). In a troubled period of English history, he contrived to rule fairly and (for a time at any rate) firmly. But in the latter part of his reign he paid more attention to his religion than to his kingdom. He died childless, and his death sparked off conflicting claims to his throne, which were resolved by the victory of William the Conqueror at the Battle of Hastings. His memory was honoured by Normans and English alike, for his fairness and his piety. Edward's mother was Norman; he had spent part of his youth in Normandy; and William claimed to have been nominated by Edward as his successor. Edward was canonized in the 12th century, and came to be venerated throughout Europe as a model of a Christian king."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Gérard de Bailleul was born about 1150. He had at least 2 sons with Helduine de BERGHES SAINT-WINOC."},"et":{"about 1150–":"umbes 1150–Surnud","1130–Female":"1130–Surnud","1150–Male":"1150–Surnud","1152–Male":"1152–Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","ABT 1150":"umbes 1150","1152":"1152","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","about 1152":"umbes 1152","Ieper,8900,Flandre Occidentale,Flandre,BELGIQUE,":"Ieper, West-Vlaanderen, Belgia"},"fi":{"about 1150–":"noin 1150–Kuollut","1130–Female":"1130–Kuollut","1150–Male":"1150–Kuollut","1152–Male":"1152–Kuollut","about 1150":"noin 1150","ABT 1150":"noin 1150","1152":"1152","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","about 1152":"noin 1152","Ieper,8900,Flandre Occidentale,Flandre,BELGIQUE,":"Ieper, West-Vlaanderen, Belgia"},"fr":{"about 1150–":"environ 1150–Décédé","1130–Female":"1130–Décédée","1150–Male":"1150–Décédé","1152–Male":"1152–Décédé","about 1150":"environ 1150","ABT 1150":"environ 1150","1152":"1152","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","about 1152":"environ 1152","Ieper,8900,Flandre Occidentale,Flandre,BELGIQUE,":"Ieper, Flandre occidentale, Belgique","lifeSummary":"Gérard de Bailleul est né environ 1150. Il a eu au moins 2 fils avec Helduine de BERGHES SAINT-WINOC."},"de":{"about 1150–":"um 1150–Verstorben","1130–Female":"1130–Verstorben","1150–Male":"1150–Verstorben","1152–Male":"1152–Verstorben","about 1150":"um 1150","ABT 1150":"um 1150","1152":"1152","1130":"1130","1150":"1150","about 1152":"um 1152","Ieper,8900,Flandre Occidentale,Flandre,BELGIQUE,":"Ieper, West-Flandern, Belgien","lifeSummary":"Géra